:: Preflight-Map [preflight]
<<set $readMap to true>>
<h3>Route Map — KSWO to KCSM</h3>

Your route takes you west-southwest across central Oklahoma. The terrain is predominantly flat agricultural land — wheat fields, cattle ranches, and section-line roads. Elevation rises gradually from about 900 ft MSL near Stillwater to 1,900 ft MSL near Clinton-Sherman.

<strong>Airports along or near the route (east to west):</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>Airport</th><th>ID</th><th>From Route</th><th>Runway</th><th>Services</th></tr>
<tr><td>Guthrie Muni</td><td>KGOK</td><td>18nm S</td><td>5,100 x 75 ft</td><td>Fuel, no maint.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Kingfisher</td><td>F92</td><td>4nm S</td><td>2,800 x 60 ft</td><td>Fuel only</td></tr>
<tr><td>Okeene (Christman)</td><td>O65</td><td>8nm N</td><td>3,000 x 60 ft</td><td>None</td></tr>
<tr><td>Enid Woodring</td><td>KWDG</td><td>32nm N</td><td>8,613 x 100 ft</td><td>Fuel, maint., ILS</td></tr>
<tr><td>Watonga Regional</td><td>KJWG</td><td>6nm S</td><td>4,001 x 60 ft</td><td>Fuel, AWOS</td></tr>
<tr><td>Clinton-Sherman</td><td>KCSM</td><td>—</td><td>13,503 x 150 ft</td><td>Full services</td></tr>
</table>

<strong>VFR Sectional — KSWO to KCSM corridor:</strong>

<div class="sectional-container">
<script id="sectional-zoom-data" type="text/plain">/scenarios/cylinder-three/images/sectional_wichita_kswo_kcsm.jpg</script>
<img src="/scenarios/cylinder-three/images/sectional_wichita_kswo_kcsm.jpg" alt="Wichita VFR Sectional — Stillwater to Clinton-Sherman corridor" onclick="openZoomChart()" style="cursor:zoom-in; max-width:100%; border:1px solid #999; border-radius:4px;">
<div class="sectional-label">Wichita Sectional (FAA, current edition) — Stillwater (KSWO) to Clinton-Sherman (KCSM)<br><em>Click to open in zoomable viewer</em></div>
</div>

<div class="chart-disclaimer"><em>This chart is provided for training and educational purposes only. It is not intended for navigation and may not reflect current aeronautical information. Always use current, officially published FAA charts and publications for flight planning and navigation.</em></div>

<strong>Terrain notes:</strong> No significant obstacles along this route. Highest obstruction is a 1,400 ft antenna farm 8nm south of Okeene (charted). Otherwise, flat to rolling agricultural land with scattered farmsteads. Section-line roads run N-S and E-W on a 1-mile grid.

[[← Back to Flight Prep|FlightPrep]]

:: Opening [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Departed KSWO, cruising at 6,500"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.08 play>><</if>>
The departure from Stillwater was textbook. Tower cleared you for a left downwind departure, you turned on course, and climbed to 6,500. Kansas City Center picked you up on flight following — "November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, radar contact, three-four miles west of Stillwater, six thousand three hundred climbing six thousand five hundred" — and the morning settled into the kind of quiet cruise that makes you remember why you fly.

Linda asked a few questions early on — what the green circles on the G1000 were, whether you could see her daughter's town from up here — and then drifted into a comfortable silence, watching the patchwork of brown and green slide past beneath you. The haze softens everything. It's a pretty morning in a plain kind of way.

You've been in cruise for about forty minutes. Kingfisher is behind you, maybe twenty miles back. The terrain below is flat and featureless — wheat stubble, section-line roads, the occasional farmstead with a silver grain bin catching the sun. Your destination is about fifty-five miles ahead. Another twenty-five minutes or so.

Then you hear it. Or rather, you feel it — a slight vibration that wasn't there before. Not a shudder. Not a bang. Just a subtle roughness in the engine note, like someone turned a smooth hum into something with texture. It comes and goes. Twenty seconds smooth, five seconds rough, twenty seconds smooth.

You look at the engine page on the G1000. Five of the six EGT bars are clustered together, right where they always are. Cylinder three is reading about fifty degrees higher than the rest. CHT on three is normal — for now.

You run a quick mag check. Right mag: normal drop, maybe fifty RPM. Left mag: the drop is a little more than usual. Seventy-five RPM, maybe eighty. The engine stumbles slightly on the left mag before settling. You switch back to both. The roughness is still there, intermittent, subtle.

The engine is making full power. The RPM is steady. The oil pressure and oil temperature are normal. Everything on the panel says this airplane is fine except for that one EGT bar and that slight catch on the left mag.

Linda looks over. "Everything okay?"

"Yeah. Just keeping an eye on something."

She nods and looks back out the window. She trusts you. She has for thirty years.

You have fifty-five miles to go. Behind you, Kingfisher's little runway is about twenty miles back. To the north, Enid Woodring is about thirty-five miles. Below you is Kingfisher County, Oklahoma — flat, open, and full of wheat fields and section-line roads. You're at 6,500 feet on a hazy morning with a rough-running engine that might be nothing and might not be.

<<link "You continue on course toward Clinton-Sherman and monitor the engine instruments closely. The engine is still making power and you're less than thirty minutes out." "A-Continue">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued on course"])>><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

<<link "You start troubleshooting — you lean the mixture aggressively to try to burn off a possible plug foul, and watch the EGT response." "B-Troubleshoot">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Began troubleshooting"])>><</link>>

<<link "You tell Kansas City Center you have a rough-running engine and want to turn back to Kingfisher — the nearest airport, about twenty miles behind you." "C-Kingfisher">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to Kingfisher"])>><</link>>

<<link "You tell Kansas City Center you have a rough-running engine and want to divert to Enid Woodring — farther away, but it has maintenance, a long runway, and an instrument approach if you need it." "D-Enid">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to Enid Woodring"])>><</link>>

<<link "You reduce power, begin a descent toward the fields below, and start looking for a place to put the airplane down while you still have altitude and options." "E-Precautionary">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Began precautionary descent"])>><</link>>

:: A-Continue [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 3000)>><</if>>
You settle your scan back into a rhythm. Airspeed, altitude, heading. Engine page. Airspeed, altitude, heading. Engine page. The roughness comes and goes — you're starting to learn its cadence, the way you learn the rhythm of turbulence on a bumpy day. It's there, and then it's not, and then it's there again.

The EGT on cylinder three hasn't moved. Still about fifty degrees above the pack. The CHT has crept up a few degrees, but it's well inside the green. Oil pressure is steady. Oil temp is steady. The engine is making the RPM you asked for.

Ten minutes pass. The roughness doesn't go away. If anything, the rough cycles are lasting a few seconds longer now — seven or eight seconds instead of five. The smooth intervals are a little shorter. It's a slow change, the kind of thing you might not notice if you weren't paying attention. But you're paying attention.

The EGT on three has climbed another twenty-five degrees. It's now seventy-five above the others. The CHT on three has come up too — not alarming, but it's separated from the pack. You can see it on the bar graph: five bars in a row, and then the sixth one, standing taller.

Linda shifts in her seat. She's been quiet, but she's noticed the vibration. "Is the engine supposed to sound like that?"

"It's running a little rough. I'm watching it."

She nods but doesn't look away from you for a few seconds. Then she turns back to the window.

You're forty-five miles from Clinton-Sherman. Kingfisher is behind you now — thirty miles or more. Enid is to the north, maybe thirty miles. Below you, the land is the same: flat, open, section-line roads, wheat stubble. The haze hasn't lifted.

<<link "You hold course. You're closer to your destination than to anywhere else, and the engine is still running. Forty-five miles. Maybe twenty minutes. You've come this far." "A1-StillContinuing">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued despite worsening"])>><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

<<link "You decide to troubleshoot now — lean the mixture, check the mags again, see if you can narrow down what's happening before you commit to a course of action." "B-Troubleshoot-Late">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Began late troubleshooting"])>><</link>>

<<link "You've seen enough. You key the mic and tell Kansas City Center you're declaring an emergency and diverting to the nearest suitable airport." "A3-DeclareEmergency">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Declared emergency and diverted"])>><</link>>

<<link "You pull the power back and start descending. You want to be closer to the ground — closer to options — while the engine is still running." "A4-LateDescend">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descended toward terrain"])>><</link>>

:: A1-StillContinuing [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" loop volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
The next ten minutes are the longest of your flying career.

The roughness is constant now. Not intermittent — constant. A steady vibration that you can feel through the yoke, through the rudder pedals, through the seat. The engine is still making power, but the RPM has dropped about thirty — not because you pulled the throttle back, but because something in the engine isn't doing what it should.

The EGT on cylinder three is now a hundred degrees above the others. The CHT on three has crossed into the upper end of the green arc. You find yourself staring at the engine page and have to force your eyes back to the airspeed indicator, the altimeter, the world outside the windshield.

Thirty-five miles to Clinton-Sherman. The terrain below has changed — the flat wheat country is giving way to slightly more rolling ground, a few more trees, the land beginning its slow rise toward the western Oklahoma plateau. The section-line roads are still there but less regular now.

Your friend has stopped looking out the window. She's looking at you. She hasn't said anything, but her hand is on the armrest.

The engine coughs. Not a sputter — a single, hard cough, like it missed a beat and then caught itself. The RPM dips and recovers. The sound smooths for a moment, then the vibration comes back, rougher than before.

<<link "You hold course. Thirty-five miles. You can see the haze thinning to the west. Clinton-Sherman has a thirteen-thousand-foot runway. You just need the engine to hold for fifteen more minutes." "A1a-FinalPress">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued a third time despite cough"])>><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

<<link "That cough just changed the math. You key the mic: 'Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, I need to declare an emergency.' You divert to the nearest suitable airport." "A1b-LateEmergency">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Declared emergency after cough"])>><</link>>

<<link "You don't call anyone yet. You pull the power back to twenty inches and start descending. You scan the terrain below for the best option you can see right now." "A1c-LateDescent">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descended after cough"])>><</link>>

:: A1a-FinalPress [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-fail" volume 0.5 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<timed 8s>><<audio "wind-quiet" loop volume 0.3 play>><</timed>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Engine failed — forced landing"])>>
Fifteen miles from Clinton-Sherman, the engine gives up.

It doesn't explode. It doesn't seize. The coughs become a stuttering rhythm, and then the RPM begins to decay — 2,200, 2,100, 2,000 — and the power just drains away, like someone slowly closing a valve. The EGT on cylinder three drops suddenly. The engine is running on five cylinders, then four, and the vibration becomes something structural, something violent.

You pull the mixture to idle cutoff. The propeller windmills in the airstream. The cockpit is suddenly, shockingly quiet.

Linda's voice is very small. "What's happening?"

"We've lost the engine. I'm going to put us down."

You're at 5,800 feet. The terrain below is rolling — not flat, not like the wheat country you were over forty minutes ago. There are trees in the draws, fences along the section lines, a ranch with outbuildings, a two-lane road that curves through a shallow valley. Nothing looks like a runway.

You pick the best option you can see — a hay field on a gentle slope, maybe a quarter mile long, bounded by a fence on the far end and a tree line to the left. You set up on a short final, gear down, full flaps, seventy knots. The hay field is coming up fast. It's shorter than it looked from altitude.

The wheels touch and the 182 decelerates hard in the tall grass. The nosewheel digs in. The airplane lurches, yaws left, and the left main gear finds a shallow ditch hidden in the grass. The gear collapses. The propeller strikes the ground. The airplane slides to a stop in a cloud of dust and torn vegetation, canted to the left, the left wing resting on the ground.

The engine is silent. The master switch is off — you don't remember turning it off, but your hands did it. Linda is next to you, breathing hard, her hand on the dashboard. The windshield is intact. You can see the sky through the dust.

"Are you okay?"

She nods. She's shaking but she's okay. You're both okay.

The airplane is not.

<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

The exhaust valve on cylinder three had been sticking intermittently, causing progressive power loss as the valve failed to seal properly. The elevated EGT was the first sign — exhaust gases leaking past the valve raised the temperature. The roughness was the valve hanging open during compression strokes. Given time, the valve stuck open permanently, and the cylinder stopped producing power. The asymmetric load on the remaining cylinders, combined with the vibration from the dead cylinder, caused progressive failure across the engine.

You had three separate opportunities to divert to a safe landing — at the first sign of roughness, when the symptoms worsened ten minutes later, and when the engine coughed. Each time, you chose to continue. By the time the engine failed, you were over terrain that offered no good emergency landing options, at an altitude that gave you limited glide range, and with no time to reach an airport.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This outcome resulted from three consecutive decisions to continue flight with a deteriorating engine. The primary hazardous attitude was <strong>invulnerability</strong> — "it's still running, it'll hold together." This was reinforced by <strong>continuation bias</strong>: each mile closer to the destination made the next mile seem more reasonable, even as the engine indicators were telling a worsening story.

The critical error was not the decision to continue at the first sign of roughness — that decision, while not optimal, was not unreasonable given the subtle symptoms. The critical error was continuing <em>after the symptoms worsened</em>, and then continuing <em>again</em> after the engine coughed. Each decision to press on consumed options — the flat terrain was behind you, the nearby airports were behind you, and the altitude you might have used for a longer glide was being spent on forward progress toward a destination you never reached.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

When an engine develops symptoms that persist and worsen over time, the trend matters more than any single data point. An EGT that's 50 degrees hot is a watch item. An EGT that's 50 degrees hot and climbing is a divert item. An engine cough after twenty minutes of deteriorating symptoms is an emergency.

The PAVE framework applies: the Pilot was capable, the Aircraft was telling you it wasn't healthy, the enVironment offered good diversion options early in the sequence, and the External pressure (a wedding) was real but not worth an airplane or a life. The time to act was when the trend became clear — at Decision Point 2, when the symptoms had worsened. Every minute past that point was borrowed time.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

An engine that is getting worse will continue to get worse. The trend is the message. Divert while you have options, altitude, and terrain — because those resources are finite and non-renewable.
</div>

