:: A1b-LateEmergency [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted under emergency — landed safely"])>>
"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, declaring an emergency. Engine running rough and deteriorating. Request vectors to nearest suitable airport. Two souls, approximately four-five gallons fuel."

There's a brief pause. "November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger your emergency. Nearest suitable airport is Watonga Regional, one-four miles to your south. Runway one-seven-three-five, four thousand one feet. AWOS available on one-one-eight-point-three-two-five. Turn left heading one-eight-zero. Emergency services are being notified."

You turn south. The engine is still running — rough, vibrating, but running. Fourteen miles. About seven minutes. You descend as you go, trading altitude for options. If the engine quits, you want to be close to the ground with the airport in sight, not high and far away.

Linda is quiet. She's holding the armrest with both hands now, but she's not panicking. She's watching you work.

Watonga appears through the haze — a single runway on flat ground, a windsock, a few hangars. You set up a straight-in approach to runway one-seven, long and stabilized, carrying extra speed. The engine coughs twice on final, and each time your hand moves toward the mixture knob. But it keeps running.

The wheels touch on Watonga's runway and you've never been so grateful for pavement. You roll to the end, clear the runway, and shut down. The engine rattles to a stop and the silence is enormous.

Linda lets out a long breath. "I need a minute."

"Take all the minutes you want."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You continued past the initial symptoms, continued again as they worsened, and finally diverted after the engine coughed — a clear sign of imminent failure. The exhaust valve on cylinder three had been progressively sticking, and by the time you declared the emergency, the engine was close to partial failure. You landed safely, but the margin was thin. A mechanic at Watonga later confirmed the valve was within minutes of sticking open permanently.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

You made two suboptimal decisions — continuing at Decision Points 1 and 2 — before making the right call at Decision Point 3. The engine cough served as an unmistakable signal that broke through the continuation bias. The hazardous attitude of <strong>invulnerability</strong> was present in the first two decisions ("it's still running"), but you recognized its limits when the situation became undeniable.

Credit is due for the emergency declaration and diversion. Once you committed to landing, your execution was sound — you maintained situational awareness, descended toward terrain options, and flew a stabilized approach. The decision to divert was correct. It was just late.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

The optimal decision point was Decision Point 2 — when the EGT had climbed further and the roughness was worsening. At that point, the trend was established and the diversion options were better (closer airports, flatter terrain, more altitude to work with). Waiting for the engine cough cost you terrain options, altitude, and time.

The DECIDE model applies: <strong>Detect</strong> the change (EGT climbing, roughness worsening), <strong>Estimate</strong> the significance (the trend is the message), <strong>Choose</strong> a course of action (divert), <strong>Identify</strong> solutions (nearest airport with AWOS and runway length), <strong>Do</strong> it, and <strong>Evaluate</strong> the result. You detected and estimated correctly at Decision Point 2 — you just didn't choose and act until Decision Point 3.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

The best time to divert is when you first recognize a worsening trend. The second-best time is right now. There is no third-best time — only luck.
</div>

