:: A1c-LateDescent [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Precautionary landing — aircraft intact"])>>
You pull the power back to eighteen inches and lower the nose. The descent begins immediately — 500 feet per minute. You're at 5,800 feet. The terrain below is more rolling than the flat country behind you, but there are still open spaces. Section-line roads. A few hay fields. A long, straight stretch of two-lane highway with no traffic visible.

You key the mic while you descend. "Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, engine running rough. We're descending for a precautionary landing approximately twenty miles east of Clinton-Sherman. Squawking seventy-seven hundred."

"Roger, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot. Emergency services notified. Say intentions."

"We'll put it down on the highway or an open field. We'll report on the ground."

Through three thousand feet. You pick the highway — it's straight for at least half a mile, running roughly north-south. The wind is from the southwest, so you'll land to the south, quartering into the wind. No power lines crossing this stretch. No vehicles.

You fly a tight pattern — downwind at a thousand feet, base turn, final. The engine is still running, still rough, still making some power. You could probably fly to Clinton-Sherman. Probably. But "probably" stopped being good enough when the engine coughed.

The wheels touch the pavement and the 182 rolls straight and true on the highway centerline. You brake gently, come to a stop, and pull off onto the gravel shoulder. The engine idles, rough and unhappy.

You shut it down.

A rancher in a pickup truck is already driving toward you from a farm house a quarter mile away. He doesn't look surprised. He looks like a man who's seen airplanes land on this road before.

Linda looks at you. "Well. You're never going to believe this, but I think that was the most impressive thing I've ever seen you do."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

After continuing through two worsening decision points, you made the decision to descend and land when the engine coughed — a clear sign of deteriorating conditions. You executed a precautionary highway landing with the engine still producing some power. The aircraft is undamaged. Both occupants are unharmed. The exhaust valve on cylinder three was later found to be sticking — had you continued, partial engine failure was likely within the next ten to fifteen minutes.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This outcome reflects a mixed decision chain. The first two decisions — to continue despite roughness and continue despite worsening — reflected <strong>continuation bias</strong> and <strong>invulnerability</strong>. The third decision — to descend and land rather than pressing the remaining thirty-five miles — was sound, and the execution was excellent.

The precautionary landing itself demonstrated good judgment: you chose a location while you still had altitude and engine power, rather than waiting for the engine to decide for you. You landed into the wind, selected a clear stretch of road, and flew a controlled approach.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

An earlier diversion — to Kingfisher, Enid, or Watonga — would have been the optimal outcome. The precautionary highway landing was safe, but it was made necessary by the two earlier decisions to continue. The ideal mental model is: "If the engine is getting worse, I should be getting closer to a runway, not farther from one."

That said, a precautionary landing executed with altitude, engine power, and good terrain selection is always a valid option. The pilot who lands in a field with a running engine will always have a better outcome than the pilot who tries for a runway and doesn't make it.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

A precautionary landing is not a failure. It's one of the best tools a pilot has — and it only works if you use it before you need it.
</div>

