:: A3-DeclareEmergency [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Declared emergency — diverted safely to Watonga"])>>
"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, declaring an emergency. Engine running rough and worsening. Two souls, four-six gallons. Request vectors to nearest suitable airport."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger your emergency. Watonga Regional is one-two miles to your southwest. Runway one-seven-three-five, four thousand one feet, AWOS on one-one-eight-point-three-two-five. Turn left heading two-one-zero. Emergency services notified."

You turn southwest. Twelve miles. Less than six minutes. The engine is rough but making power. You descend as you go — every foot of altitude toward Watonga is a foot you don't need the engine for.

Watonga's runway appears through the haze, and you've never been happier to see four thousand feet of concrete. You fly a straight-in approach, carry a few extra knots for the gust factor, and put the 182 on the numbers.

The landing is smooth. The rollout is uneventful. You taxi to the ramp and shut down.

Linda looks at you. "Is this Weatherford?"

"No. This is Watonga. The engine wasn't running right, so I landed here. We're about thirty miles from the wedding."

"Okay." She pauses. "Good."

The AWOS is broadcasting: wind three-two-zero at twelve, visibility eight. A nice day for a drive to a wedding. You call a cab company, and then you call an A&P mechanic in Enid. The airplane will be here when you come back for it.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

After continuing past the initial roughness and seeing the symptoms worsen over the next ten minutes, you recognized the trend and declared an emergency. You diverted to Watonga Regional, the nearest airport with a suitable runway and weather reporting, and landed without incident.

The mechanic who examined the engine the following day found a sticking exhaust valve on cylinder three. Had you continued to Clinton-Sherman — another forty-five miles — the valve would likely have stuck open permanently, causing partial engine failure over less favorable terrain.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

Your first decision — to continue at Decision Point 1 — was not unreasonable given the subtle, intermittent nature of the initial symptoms. The critical good judgment came at Decision Point 2: when the symptoms worsened, you recognized the trend, broke the continuation bias, and acted decisively. Declaring an emergency was appropriate and ensured priority handling.

The ten-minute delay between the initial symptoms and the diversion decision cost some terrain advantage (you were over flatter country earlier) but did not materially affect the outcome. The earlier you recognize a worsening trend and act on it, the more options you preserve.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This is close to optimal. The only improvement would have been to divert at the first sign of roughness — but the ambiguity of the initial symptoms (possible fouled plug, intermittent, engine making full power) makes the "monitor and continue" decision defensible at Decision Point 1. What made the difference was that you didn't let "monitor and continue" become the permanent plan. When the data changed, you changed your decision.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

There is no shame in an emergency declaration. It's a tool, not a confession. Use it early, and the story ends with an inconvenience instead of an accident.
</div>

