:: A4-LateDescend [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descended and made precautionary landing"])>>
You pull the power back slowly and lower the nose. Five hundred feet per minute. You're at 6,200 feet, and the ground is at about 1,200 feet elevation here — five thousand feet of altitude to work with.

"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, engine running rough. We're descending for a precautionary landing. Squawking seventy-seven hundred."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Nearest airport is Watonga Regional, one-one miles to your southwest. Do you want vectors?"

You look at the G1000. Watonga is eleven miles. You have altitude to get there, and the engine is still running. "Affirmative. Vectors to Watonga."

"Turn left heading two-one-zero. Watonga altimeter three-zero-zero-one."

You fly to Watonga with the engine making power and the vibration constant in the airframe. The descent puts you at pattern altitude right at the field. You land on runway one-seven, roll out, and taxi to the ramp. The engine runs at idle, rough but alive.

You shut down and sit for a moment.

Linda reaches over and puts her hand on your arm. "Thank you."

"For what?"

"For not pretending everything was fine."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

After continuing past the initial symptoms, you recognized the worsening trend and chose to descend — prioritizing proximity to the ground and landing options. When ATC offered vectors to Watonga Regional (eleven miles away), you accepted, and landed safely with the engine still running.

Post-landing inspection revealed a sticking exhaust valve on cylinder three. The engine was producing power but on a declining trajectory. Your decision to descend and land preserved the margin that a continued cruise to Clinton-Sherman would have consumed.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

You made one suboptimal decision (continuing at Decision Point 1) and then corrected at Decision Point 2. The choice to descend — putting yourself closer to terrain options — demonstrated good risk management. Accepting ATC's suggestion of Watonga rather than insisting on a field landing showed appropriate flexibility.

The hazardous attitude of <strong>invulnerability</strong> was present at Decision Point 1, but it did not persist. When the situation changed, you changed your plan.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This was a solid recovery from an initially conservative "wait and see" posture. The key strength was recognizing that descending toward options — even before declaring a formal emergency — put you in a fundamentally better position. Altitude is a resource. Spending it on proximity to landing options is always a good trade when the engine is in question.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

When in doubt about the engine, trade altitude for options. The ground is where you're going to end up either way — the question is whether you get there on your terms or the engine's.
</div>

