<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: B-Troubleshoot [scenario branch-b]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 2000)>><</if>>
You reach for the mixture knob and pull it back — slowly, deliberately, leaning the engine well past where you'd normally set it in cruise. The EGTs climb across the board, all six cylinders running hotter as the fuel flow drops. You watch the engine analyzer.

For about thirty seconds, the roughness smooths out. The vibration fades. The engine hums, clean and steady, the way it did an hour ago. You almost convince yourself you've fixed it.

Then it comes back. A slight unevenness, building over a few seconds until the same intermittent roughness is right where it was before. Cylinder three's EGT is still the outlier — it climbed with the leaning but maintained its gap above the others. You enrich the mixture back to best power.

You try cycling the left magneto. Off, wait two seconds, back on. The engine sags on one mag and recovers. The roughness doesn't change. You try the right mag — off and back on. No difference.

Three minutes of troubleshooting, and you know a little more than you did. The leaning helped temporarily, which is consistent with a fouled plug. But it didn't fix it, which means it might not be a fouled plug. The mag check still shows that extra drop on the left. You haven't ruled out anything.

What you have done is spend three minutes heads-down on the engine page. When you look up, you realize you've drifted about two miles south of your course line. The G1000 is showing the magenta line to your right. It's not a problem — there's nothing out here to hit — but it's a reminder that troubleshooting cost you some of your scan.

Linda is watching you work the knobs and switches. She doesn't ask. She can tell this isn't casual.

You're fifty-five miles from Clinton-Sherman. Kingfisher is twenty miles behind you. Enid is thirty-five to the north. The engine is still making power. The roughness persists.

<<link "The leaning helped for a moment — that points to a fouled plug. You continue to your destination and plan to have a mechanic look at it after you land." "B1-ContinueBadDiag">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diagnosed as fouled plug — continued"])>><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

<<link "You lean the mixture again and leave it leaned aggressively, hoping sustained heat will burn the plug clean. You continue on course." "B2-LeanBurn">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Sustained lean burn — continued"])>><</link>>

<<link "You didn't fix it and you can't diagnose it from up here. You tell Kansas City Center you want to divert to Enid Woodring — the closest airport with a mechanic." "B3-DivertEnid">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to Enid after troubleshooting"])>><</link>>

<<link "You tell Kansas City Center you have a rough-running engine and request vectors to the nearest suitable airport with maintenance." "B4-DivertNearest">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Requested nearest maintenance airport"])>><</link>>

:: B-Troubleshoot-Late [scenario branch-b]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" loop volume 0.45 play>><</if>>
You lean the mixture, just as you would have ten minutes ago. The same thing happens — the roughness smooths for thirty seconds, then comes back. But this time, the baseline is worse. The vibration during the rough cycles is more pronounced, and the smooth intervals are shorter.

You've confirmed what you suspected: the problem isn't going away, and the troubleshooting that would have been merely inconclusive earlier is now actively telling you the situation is deteriorating.

Linda watches you adjust the mixture. "Did that help?"

"Not enough."

You're forty-five miles from Clinton-Sherman. Enid is thirty miles to the north. Watonga is about twelve miles to the southwest. The engine is making power, but less confidently than it was twenty minutes ago.

<<link "You tell Kansas City Center you want to divert to the nearest suitable airport. No more troubleshooting." "B4-DivertNearest">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted after late troubleshooting"])>><</link>>

<<link "The leaning helped briefly. It's probably a plug. You continue to Clinton-Sherman — you're closer to the destination now than to Enid." "B1-ContinueBadDiag">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diagnosed as plug — continued after late troubleshooting"])>><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

:: B1-ContinueBadDiag [scenario branch-b ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Engine partially failed on approach"])>>
You press on toward Clinton-Sherman, watching the engine page like it's the only instrument in the airplane. The roughness continues. The EGT on three stays high. The CHT is climbing slowly. But the engine is making power, and the miles are counting down.

Forty miles. Thirty. Twenty-five. You can almost convince yourself the roughness isn't getting worse.

At fifteen miles, you begin your descent. Clinton-Sherman's thirteen-thousand-foot runway is ahead of you in the haze. You can see the long concrete strip, incongruously huge in the middle of ranch country. You begin to relax.

At eight miles, on a shallow descent through three thousand feet AGL, the engine coughs hard. Three quick coughs in succession, and the RPM drops a hundred. It recovers, but the power isn't all there anymore. The airspeed is decaying. The descent rate is increasing.

You push the nose down to maintain airspeed and key the mic. "Clinton-Sherman traffic, Cessna four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, eight mile final runway one-seven, engine running rough, declaring emergency."

The runway is ahead. The engine is making partial power — enough to fly, not enough to climb. You're descending whether you want to or not. The 182 crosses the threshold at sixty-five knots — five below the normal approach speed — and you flare late, still fast for the conditions. The mains hit hard. The nosewheel slams down. The airplane bounces, settles, and rolls.

You're on the runway. You brake to a stop and sit there, shaking slightly. The engine idles, rough and rattling.

Linda is gripping the seat. "Are we okay?"

"We're on the ground."

The hard landing will need an inspection. The nose gear took a hit. The firewall may have damage. The airplane flew you here, but it didn't enjoy the last mile.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You diagnosed the engine roughness as a probable fouled plug based on the temporary improvement during leaning. This diagnosis was plausible but incorrect — the actual problem was a sticking exhaust valve on cylinder three, a progressive mechanical failure that was never going to respond to leaning or burn off in flight.

By continuing to the destination on an unconfirmed diagnosis, you arrived at Clinton-Sherman with a partially failing engine. The hard landing resulted in potential airframe damage — a nosewheel gear inspection and possible firewall damage from the impact. Both occupants are unharmed, but the aircraft will need significant inspection before returning to service.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

The primary error was <strong>diagnostic anchoring</strong> — forming a hypothesis (fouled plug) based on limited evidence and then treating that hypothesis as a confirmed diagnosis. The temporary improvement during leaning was consistent with a fouled plug, but it was also consistent with other, more serious causes. The troubleshooting gave you information, but not a conclusion. Treating it as a conclusion was the error.

The hazardous attitude was a subtle form of <strong>invulnerability</strong>: "I've figured out what's wrong, so I don't need to worry." This is more dangerous than simple denial because it feels like good airmanship. You did the work. You tested the hypothesis. You just didn't stay open to the possibility that you were wrong.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

Troubleshooting in flight is appropriate and useful. But the result of inconclusive troubleshooting should be a diversion, not a continuation. The correct mental model is: "I tried to diagnose it, and I couldn't confirm the diagnosis. Therefore, I should land where someone with tools and a hangar can confirm it."

If the leaning had permanently resolved the roughness — smooth engine, normal EGT, normal mag check — continuing would have been defensible. But "it helped for thirty seconds and came back" is not a diagnosis. It's a data point.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

A hypothesis is not a diagnosis. If you can't confirm the problem from the cockpit, land where someone can confirm it from the shop.
</div>

