<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: B2-LeanBurn [scenario branch-b ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" loop volume 0.5 play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Sustained lean burn — engine worsened"])>>
You pull the mixture back again — further this time — and leave it there. The EGTs climb across the board. The engine smooths out, just like before. You hold the lean mixture and continue on course, watching the engine page, waiting to see if the sustained heat will clean whatever is fouling that plug.

Five minutes pass. The engine runs smoother at the aggressive lean setting. The roughness is gone. Cylinder three's EGT is still higher than the others, but the gap has narrowed. You start to think this might actually work.

Then the CHT on cylinder three begins to climb. Slowly at first, then more noticeably. The aggressive lean is running that cylinder very hot. If this were a fouled plug, the lean burn would be clearing it. But the plug isn't the problem — the exhaust valve is, and the extra heat from the lean mixture is making a mechanical problem worse.

At ten minutes, the roughness returns despite the leaning. It's worse now. The CHT on three is in the yellow arc — not red, but higher than you've ever seen it. You enrich the mixture and the roughness gets worse as the lean burn stops masking the symptoms. The engine is shaking. The RPM drops thirty.

You've made it worse.

You key the mic. "Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, declaring an emergency. Engine failure in progress. Request vectors to nearest airport."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, Watonga Regional, one-zero miles to your south. Turn left heading one-eight-zero."

You make Watonga. Barely. The engine is making maybe sixty percent power by the time you cross the threshold, and the approach is steep and fast. You land hard but on pavement, and the airplane rolls to a stop with the engine rattling like a box of loose hardware at idle.

A mechanic in Enid will later find the exhaust valve on cylinder three galled and partially welded to the seat — heat damage consistent with sustained operation at excessively lean mixtures with a valve that was already compromised.

Linda is white-faced but intact. "Let's drive to the wedding."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

The sustained lean burn temporarily masked the symptoms but accelerated the underlying failure. The sticking exhaust valve was already compromised; running the cylinder at elevated temperatures for an extended period caused thermal damage to the valve and seat. The engine deteriorated faster than it would have at normal mixture settings.

You arrived at Watonga under emergency conditions with a severely compromised engine. Both occupants are safe. The aircraft will require an engine teardown — the thermal damage to cylinder three may extend to adjacent components.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

The troubleshooting itself was reasonable — leaning to test for a fouled plug is standard practice. The error was in the follow-up: when the lean burn didn't produce a lasting fix, treating it as an ongoing treatment rather than recognizing it as a failed test. Leaving the mixture aggressively leaned is appropriate for a confirmed fouled plug. For an unconfirmed diagnosis, it's a gamble — and in this case, it worsened the actual problem.

This is a case of <strong>plan continuation after treatment failure</strong>: "I've started the fix, so I should keep going with it." The mental model should have been: "If the lean burn doesn't permanently resolve the roughness within two to three minutes, it's not a plug. Return to normal mixture and divert."

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

Time-box your troubleshooting. Lean to test for a fouled plug. If the roughness resolves and stays resolved after you return to normal mixture — it was a plug. If it comes back, stop treating and start diverting. Leaving the mixture aggressively leaned "just in case" is treating a symptom without confirming the disease, and it carries the risk of making a mechanical problem worse through thermal stress.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

Troubleshooting is a test, not a treatment. If the test doesn't produce a clear answer, stop testing and start landing.
</div>

