:: B3-DivertEnid [scenario branch-b ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to Enid — landed safely, mechanic found valve"])>>
"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot. We've got a rough-running engine. Tried troubleshooting, can't confirm the cause. We'd like to divert to Enid Woodring for maintenance."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Turn right heading zero-three-zero for Enid Woodring, three-five miles. Squawk seven-seven-zero-zero. Enid altimeter three-zero-zero-one."

You turn north. The engine continues its rough rhythm. Thirty-five miles to a long runway, a mechanic, and an answer.

The flight to Enid is uneventful — the roughness continues but doesn't worsen. You contact Enid Tower, report the rough engine, and they clear you straight in for runway three-five. The crosswind is there — gusting to twenty-two — but the 8,600-foot runway gives you all the room you need. You land, taxi to the FBO, and shut down.

The A&P on duty comes out within ten minutes. You describe the symptoms — the EGT, the mag check, the response to leaning. He nods. "Let me pull the cowl."

Forty-five minutes later, he has the answer. "Exhaust valve on cylinder three. It's sticking. You can see the carbon buildup on the seat. It would have gotten worse." He pauses. "Good call coming in here."

You call Linda's daughter. You'll be a few hours late. You rent a car from the FBO and point it west toward Weatherford.

Linda, in the passenger seat of the rental car, looks over at you. "I liked the way you handled that."

"I didn't like not knowing what was wrong."

"That's exactly what I mean."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You attempted to troubleshoot the engine roughness in flight. The leaning test was inconclusive — temporary improvement followed by recurrence, consistent with a fouled plug but not confirmatory. Rather than treating the inconclusive result as a diagnosis, you recognized the limits of what you could determine from the cockpit and diverted to the nearest airport with maintenance capability.

The mechanic at Enid Woodring found a sticking exhaust valve on cylinder three — a progressive mechanical failure that would have worsened in flight and could not have been resolved by any in-flight troubleshooting procedure. Your decision to divert after inconclusive troubleshooting was the correct response to ambiguity.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This is strong decision-making under uncertainty. You gathered information (troubleshooting), evaluated the results honestly (inconclusive), and acted appropriately (diverted to maintenance). The key strength was <strong>intellectual honesty</strong>: you did not allow a plausible but unconfirmed hypothesis to become the basis for continuing flight.

No hazardous attitudes were present in the decision chain. The troubleshooting was appropriate, the interpretation was sound, and the action was decisive.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This is what good judgment looks like. Troubleshoot when you can. Recognize the limits of in-flight diagnosis. When you can't confirm the cause, land where someone can. The decision to divert after inconclusive troubleshooting — rather than after the situation worsened — is exactly the kind of proactive risk management that prevents accidents.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

Not knowing what's wrong is itself a reason to land. You don't need a diagnosis to justify a diversion — you need one to justify continuing.
</div>

