:: B4-DivertNearest [scenario branch-b ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["ATC vectored to Watonga — landed safely"])>>
"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, engine running rough. Unable to resolve in flight. Request vectors to nearest suitable airport with maintenance capability."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Enid Woodring is three-five miles to your north with maintenance available. Watonga Regional is one-two miles to your southwest, runway four thousand one feet, but no maintenance on field. Say preference."

You think about it. Twelve miles versus thirty-five. "We'll take Watonga. We can arrange maintenance from there."

"Roger. Turn left heading two-one-zero for Watonga Regional. Altimeter three-zero-zero-one."

Twelve miles. Six minutes. The engine roughness continues, unchanged. You land at Watonga without incident, shut down, and start making phone calls. An A&P from Enid comes out that afternoon. Sticking exhaust valve, cylinder three. The airplane is grounded for repair.

You rent a car and make the wedding with time to spare.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You chose the practical option: land at the nearest suitable airport and arrange maintenance from the ground. The twelve-mile flight to Watonga minimized time in the air with a rough engine, and the longer runway and AWOS made it a sound choice. Maintenance was arranged from Enid.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

Sound decision-making throughout. You troubleshot the engine (appropriate), recognized the limits of your diagnosis (honest), and chose to minimize exposure by landing at the nearest airport rather than flying an additional twenty-three miles to Enid. The choice to accept Watonga over Enid — closer with adequate facilities, even without on-field maintenance — reflected good risk prioritization: get on the ground first, solve the maintenance problem second.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This is an excellent example of separating the immediate problem (rough engine, land now) from the secondary problem (need a mechanic, solve on the ground). Pilots sometimes fly past a perfectly good airport to reach one with better services — adding risk to solve a logistics problem. You avoided that trap.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

Land first, solve problems second. The best airport for an engine problem is the closest one you can land at safely. Maintenance can come to you.
</div>

