:: C-Kingfisher [scenario branch-c]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 2000)>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
You key the mic. "Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we've got a rough-running engine. We'd like to turn around and divert to Kingfisher, about twenty miles behind us."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger rough engine. Kingfisher is at your six o'clock, two-zero miles. Squawk seven-seven-zero-zero, say souls on board and fuel remaining."

"Two souls, approximately four-eight gallons. Squawking seventy-seven hundred."

"Copy, two souls, four-eight gallons. Be advised Kingfisher is unattended, runway one-eight-three-six, two thousand eight hundred feet. Nearest field with services is Enid Woodring, three-two miles to your north. Say intentions."

There it is. ATC just laid out your options, matter-of-fact. The little runway behind you, or the big one to the north. You've already said Kingfisher.

"We'll take Kingfisher. November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot."

"Roger. Radar services terminated, squawk VFR, frequency change approved. Kingfisher CTAF is one-two-two-point-nine. Good luck."

You turn the airplane around. The sun is in your face now. The roughness continues — same cadence, same character, nothing worse. Twenty miles back the way you came. About ten minutes.

The flight to Kingfisher is uneventful. The engine does what it's been doing — rough, smooth, rough, smooth — but it doesn't get worse. You descend to pattern altitude, overfly the field. The runway is oriented north-south, a strip of concrete in the middle of farmland. A single row of T-hangars on the east side. A windsock at the south end, showing about fifteen knots from the southwest — a crosswind, maybe thirty degrees off the runway heading.

The runway is 2,800 feet long. You've landed on shorter. But not with a crosswind and not with an engine you don't trust. You set up for a long, stabilized final approach to runway one-eight, carrying a little extra speed for the gust factor.

The landing is fine. Firm, but fine. The crosswind pushes you but you hold the centerline. You roll out and taxi clear. The engine runs steady at idle. At a thousand RPM on the ground, it sounds perfectly normal.

Linda lets out a breath she's apparently been holding. "Well. That was exciting."

You park the airplane on a gravel tiedown area near the hangars. There's a fuel pump, a courtesy phone on the wall of a small block building, and not much else. No one seems to be around. The windsock flaps. A truck passes on the road beyond the fence.

<<link "You shut down, secure the airplane, and start making phone calls. First call: an A&P in Enid who can come take a look. Second call: Linda's daughter. You're done flying until a mechanic says it's safe." "C1-WaitForMechanic">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Secured aircraft, called mechanic"])>><</link>>

<<link "You run the engine up on the ground. Full power — it sounds smooth. Mag check — normal. Whatever it was, it seems to have cleared. You consider departing again." "C2-GroundRunUp">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ran engine on ground — sounded normal"])>><</link>>

<<link "You shut down and don't even think about the engine. You call the FBO at Enid and arrange a ride. You and Linda will drive to the wedding. The airplane stays until a mechanic clears it." "C3-DoneFlying">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Grounded aircraft, arranged ground transport"])>><</link>>

:: C1-WaitForMechanic [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Mechanic found sticking valve — aircraft grounded"])>>
You shut down, pull the mixture to cutoff, turn off the master. The propeller ticks to a stop. The wind blows across the ramp.

You pull out your phone. The first call is to the FBO at Enid Woodring. "Hi, I just landed at Kingfisher with a rough-running engine. Do you have an A&P who could come take a look? ... Cylinder three EGT was elevated, slight drop on the left mag, intermittent roughness in cruise that didn't respond to leaning."

They have a mechanic. He can be there in about an hour.

The second call is to Linda's daughter. "Hey, sweetheart. We're fine, but we had to land at a little airport about halfway there. The engine was acting up. We're going to be late — maybe a few hours. We'll figure out a ride." You can hear the concern in her voice, and the relief when you explain that you're on the ground and safe.

Linda sits on a bench outside the small block building and calls her daughter back herself. You can hear her voice, calm and matter-of-fact: "Your mom's friend is a very careful pilot. We're fine. We'll be there."

The mechanic arrives in a white pickup truck from Enid. He's a quiet man with oil-stained hands and a look that says he's seen everything. He pulls the cowl, checks the plugs, runs a borescope into the cylinders. Twenty minutes later, he straightens up.

"Exhaust valve on three. It's sticking. See this?" He shows you the borescope image on his phone — carbon buildup on the valve seat, scoring on the guide. "It's been getting worse for a while. It would have stuck open eventually. Might have been today, might have been next flight." He pauses. "This airplane is grounded until I replace that valve."

You nod. You already knew that was the answer, even if you didn't know the specifics.

You rent a car from a farmer down the road who's happy to earn fifty dollars. You and Linda drive to Weatherford. You make the rehearsal dinner. The wedding is beautiful. The airplane gets a new valve and is flying again by Wednesday.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

At the first sign of engine trouble, you diverted to the nearest airport and arranged for professional maintenance. The mechanic confirmed a sticking exhaust valve on cylinder three — a progressive failure that would have continued to worsen in flight. Your aircraft was safely on the ground when the diagnosis was made, and the repair was completed without incident.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This is excellent aeronautical decision-making. You recognized an anomaly, assessed the risk, and acted conservatively. You did not attempt to diagnose the problem yourself beyond the initial cockpit observations. You did not attempt to continue flight after landing. You treated the ambiguity of the situation as a reason to land, not a reason to continue.

No hazardous attitudes were present. The social pressure (a wedding) existed, but you managed it by communicating early — calling ahead, setting expectations, and arranging alternative transportation. The wedding was never in jeopardy; only the airplane was.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This is what it looks like. Detect the anomaly. Land. Get a professional to look at it. Solve the transportation problem on the ground. The willingness to accept the inconvenience of a diversion — the farmer's car, the late arrival, the grounded airplane — is the hallmark of a pilot who will have a long flying career.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

The best pilots are the ones who make the boring decision. Divert, land, call a mechanic. It's not dramatic. It's not cinematic. It's safe.
</div>

