:: C2-GroundRunUp [scenario branch-c]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-rough", "engine-smooth", 2000)>><</if>>
You sit in the airplane with the engine at idle, listening. It sounds... normal. Completely normal. The smooth, steady idle of a Continental IO-540 with nothing wrong.

You push the throttle up slowly. Fifteen hundred RPM. Smooth. Eighteen hundred. Smooth. You do a full run-up — twenty-two hundred RPM, mag check: left drops fifty, right drops forty-five. Textbook. You cycle the prop. Everything behaves exactly as it should.

You pull the throttle back to idle and sit there for a moment, looking at the engine page. Every EGT bar is in line. Every CHT is normal. The oil pressure and temperature are right where the book says they should be. The airplane is sitting on the ground at Kingfisher, sounding like it just rolled out of annual.

Linda is watching you. She's smart enough to know what you're thinking.

"Is it fixed?"

"It... ran fine on the ground just now."

"But it wasn't fine in the air."

"No. It wasn't fine in the air."

There's a long pause. You can hear the wind against the airplane and the distant sound of a tractor.

<<link "You shut down. If it ran rough in the air, it's not fixed just because it runs smooth on the ground. You secure the airplane and call for a mechanic." "C2a-ShutDown">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Recognized ground run-up inconclusive — shut down"])>><</link>>

<<link "The run-up was clean. Maybe it was a fouled plug that burned off. You decide to depart — you'll keep a close eye on the instruments, and if it starts again, Enid is twenty miles to the north." "C2b-DepartAgain">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Departed Kingfisher despite earlier roughness"])>><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

:: C2a-ShutDown [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Grounded aircraft after ground run-up — mechanic confirmed valve"])>>
You pull the mixture to cutoff. The engine winds down and stops.

"We're staying?"

"We're staying. Something made that engine run rough at altitude, and a clean run-up on the ground doesn't tell me it won't do it again at six thousand five hundred feet. I'm calling a mechanic."

Linda nods. She doesn't argue. She's been watching you make decisions all morning, and she's noticed something: you've been making the careful ones.

The mechanic from Enid arrives ninety minutes later. He finds the sticking exhaust valve. "It'll stick intermittently," he explains. "Ground run at sea level, lower cylinder pressures, it might seat fine. Get it up to altitude, higher manifold pressures, higher temperatures — that's when it starts hanging up." He looks at you. "You were smart not to take off again."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You diverted to Kingfisher at the first sign of trouble — good. The engine ran clean on the ground, creating a strong temptation to depart. You recognized that a clean ground run-up does not clear an in-flight anomaly and chose to remain on the ground until a mechanic could examine the engine.

The mechanic confirmed a sticking exhaust valve that was intermittent and altitude-dependent. The ground run-up was not diagnostic because the conditions that triggered the valve sticking (higher altitude, higher manifold pressures, higher temperatures) were not present on the ground.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This is outstanding judgment. The hardest decision in this scenario is not the initial diversion — it's the decision to stay on the ground after the engine runs clean. The temptation to depart is enormous: the run-up was normal, the airplane sounds fine, the wedding is waiting, and you're sitting at a little airport in the middle of nowhere with nothing to do but wait.

The key insight you demonstrated is that <strong>a ground run-up cannot clear an in-flight anomaly</strong>. Engine problems that manifest at altitude, under load, at temperature — these problems can disappear at idle on the ground and return the moment you climb back to cruise. A clean run-up tells you the engine runs clean at 2,200 RPM on the ground. It tells you nothing about what it will do at 6,500 feet.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

Exactly this. Divert, land, resist the temptation to take off again, and wait for a professional diagnosis. The ability to distinguish between "the problem went away" and "the conditions that caused the problem went away" is a mark of genuine expertise.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

A clean ground run-up after an in-flight engine anomaly does not mean the problem is resolved. It means the conditions that caused the problem are not currently present. Only a mechanic can tell you whether they'll return.
</div>

