<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C2b-DepartAgain [scenario branch-c ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Engine roughness returned — diverted to Enid"])>>
You taxi back to runway one-eight and do one more run-up. Clean. Normal. You take the runway, apply power, and the 182 accelerates smoothly. Rotation, climb, and you turn on course toward Clinton-Sherman.

For ten minutes, the engine is perfect. Smooth, quiet, making power. You start to relax. Linda starts to relax. The haze is thinning to the west, and you can see further now.

Then, passing through four thousand five hundred feet, it comes back. The same roughness. The same vibration. The same EGT on cylinder three, fifty degrees above the pack and climbing.

You don't hesitate. Not this time.

"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, engine roughness has returned. Diverting to Enid Woodring. Squawking seventy-seven hundred."

You turn north. Enid is twenty miles. The engine is doing exactly what it did before — rough, intermittent, and not getting better. But this time you know something you didn't know before: whatever this problem is, it isn't a fouled plug, and it isn't going away.

You land at Enid without incident. The mechanic finds the valve. The airplane is grounded.

Linda, in the FBO pilot lounge, hands you a cup of coffee. "I was wondering if you were going to take off again."

"I shouldn't have."

"No. But you figured it out."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

After diverting to Kingfisher and finding the engine ran clean on the ground, you departed to continue to your destination. The engine roughness returned at altitude, confirming that the problem was altitude-dependent and not a simple fouled plug. You diverted immediately to Enid Woodring, where the mechanic found the sticking exhaust valve.

Both occupants are safe. The aircraft is undamaged. But the second departure from Kingfisher was an unnecessary exposure to risk.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

The initial diversion to Kingfisher was sound. The error was departing again based on a clean ground run-up — treating the absence of symptoms on the ground as evidence that the problem was resolved. This is a common and understandable error, but it is an error.

The saving grace was the <strong>immediate diversion</strong> when the roughness returned. You did not repeat the "continue and monitor" pattern. The lesson was learned in real time, and you acted on it. This represents good <strong>cognitive flexibility</strong> — the ability to update your mental model when new information contradicts your previous decision.

The hazardous attitude was a brief episode of <strong>invulnerability</strong>: "it's running fine now, so it must be fine." This was corrected when the evidence proved otherwise.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

The optimal decision at Kingfisher was to remain on the ground and call a mechanic — the same as if the run-up had shown a problem. An in-flight anomaly is not cleared by a ground run-up; it is cleared by a mechanic with tools. The departure from Kingfisher turned a completed diversion into a second flight with a known (but temporarily dormant) problem.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

When an engine runs rough in the air and smooth on the ground, trust the air. The problem isn't gone — it's waiting for the conditions that caused it. Stay on the ground.
</div>

