<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C3-DoneFlying [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Arranged ground transport — airplane stays"])>>
You don't even run the engine up. You shut down, tie down, and pull out your phone.

"What are you doing?" Linda asks.

"Finding us a ride to Weatherford. This airplane stays here until a mechanic tells me what's wrong with it."

"What about after the wedding?"

"We'll figure that out after the wedding."

You call the Enid Woodring FBO. They can send a courtesy car to Kingfisher — it'll take about forty-five minutes. You call a mechanic in Enid and describe the symptoms. He says he'll drive out to Kingfisher tomorrow. You call Linda's daughter and let her know you'll be late but you're coming by car.

Ninety minutes later, you and Linda are on Highway 33 headed west in a borrowed sedan, and the airplane is sitting on a gravel tiedown in Kingfisher with a note taped to the panel: "DO NOT FLY — ENGINE ISSUE — MECHANIC COMING."

The wedding is wonderful. The mechanic finds the sticking valve on Sunday morning. The airplane flies home the following Thursday with a new valve and a clean bill of health.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

At the first sign of engine trouble, you diverted to the nearest airport, secured the aircraft, and arranged ground transportation. You did not run the engine on the ground, did not consider departing again, and did not attempt to diagnose the problem yourself. You treated the airplane as grounded until a qualified mechanic could examine it.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This is the most conservative outcome in the scenario, and it is excellent. The decision not to even run the engine on the ground eliminated the temptation of a clean run-up. The decision to arrange a mechanic and ground transportation simultaneously demonstrated practical problem-solving — separating the "get to the wedding" problem from the "fix the airplane" problem and solving each independently.

No hazardous attitudes were present. The social pressure of the wedding was managed through early communication and alternative planning.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

Sometimes the best aeronautical decision-making looks nothing like flying. It looks like a phone call, a borrowed car, and an airplane sitting on a ramp with a note on the panel. The pilot who can walk away from an airplane without feeling like they've failed is the pilot who will be flying for a long time.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

The airplane is a tool. When the tool isn't working, put it down and pick up a different one. There is always another way to get where you're going.
</div>

