<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: D-Enid [scenario branch-d]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 2000)>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
You key the mic. "Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we've got a rough-running engine. We'd like to divert to Enid Woodring for maintenance."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger rough engine. Turn right heading zero-three-zero for Enid Woodring Regional, three-five miles. Squawk seven-seven-zero-zero. Say souls on board and fuel remaining."

"Two souls, four-eight gallons. Squawking seventy-seven hundred."

"Copy. Enid altimeter three-zero-zero-one. Enid weather: ceiling four thousand five hundred broken, visibility eight in haze, wind three-two-zero at one-four gusting two-two. Enid tower on one-one-eight-point-nine. ILS runway three-five and RNAV runway one-seven available. Say approach request."

You think about that wind. Three-two-zero at fourteen gusting twenty-two. That's almost a direct crosswind on runway one-seven, and a quartering headwind on three-five. You've landed in worse, but not with a rough engine splitting your attention.

"We'll plan a visual to runway three-five. November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot."

"Roger. Contact Enid Tower on one-one-eight-point-nine in about ten miles. I'll leave you on this frequency until then."

The turn to the north puts the wind more on your tail, and the groundspeed climbs. Thirty-five miles. At this speed, maybe fifteen minutes. The engine roughness continues — unchanged. The EGT on three is still elevated, the mag check still shows that extra drop on the left, but nothing is getting worse. The airplane is flying. It just doesn't sound right.

Linda watches the G1000 map. She can see the airport symbol getting closer. "Is that where we're going?"

"That's Enid. Good runway, and they have a mechanic. We'll get this looked at before we go any further."

"What about the rehearsal dinner?"

"We'll make it. Just might be a few hours late."

She doesn't argue.

Fifteen minutes of rough engine over flat country. You monitor the instruments and watch the numbers tick down. Twenty miles. Fifteen. Ten. Kansas City Center hands you off to Enid Tower. You check in and report the rough engine. The tower clears you straight in for runway three-five, number one.

The approach is uneventful. The crosswind from the northwest pushes you around on final, and the gusts make the last two hundred feet bumpy, but the 182 handles it. You plant the mains on the big concrete runway and roll long, because you have eight thousand feet and there's no reason to brake hard. The engine runs at idle, rough but running, all the way to the FBO ramp.

A lineman is waiting for you. He's seen the squawk code. "Rough engine?"

"Cylinder three. EGT's been running high, slight mag drop on the left."

He nods. "We've got an A&P here today. Want him to take a look?"

<<link "'Yes. Please. We're not going anywhere until someone tells me what's going on with that engine.' You shut down and start helping Linda with the bags." "D1-MechanicLook">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Requested mechanic at Enid — grounded aircraft"])>><</link>>

<<link "You hesitate. The engine ran fine at idle on the taxi. Part of you is thinking about the rehearsal dinner, the hotel reservation, the drive from Enid to Weatherford. 'Can he look at it quickly? We're trying to get to Clinton-Sherman today.'" "D2-QuickLook">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Asked for quick look — wanted to continue"])>><</link>>

:: D1-MechanicLook [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Mechanic confirmed valve — aircraft grounded, rented car"])>>
The A&P is a woman named Linda with silver-streaked hair and forearms that suggest she's been pulling wrenches longer than you've been flying. She listens to your description — the EGT, the mag check, the intermittent roughness, the response to leaning — and nods without expression.

"Let me pull the top cowl. Go get some coffee. This'll take about thirty minutes."

You and Linda find the pilot lounge. There's coffee, a vending machine, and a couch that's seen better decades. Linda calls her daughter. You call the rental car company.

Linda comes back wiping her hands. "Exhaust valve on three. Sticking intermittent — you can see the carbon scoring on the seat and guide. It's not going to get better. I need to pull the cylinder and replace the valve, reseat it, and do a compression check before this airplane goes anywhere."

"How long?"

"Parts, two days minimum. I'll have it back to you by Thursday if I can get the valve from Tulsa."

You nod. It's what you expected. "Thank you."

"Thank you for landing here instead of trying to make Clinton-Sherman. I see the ones who try to make it, too. Those conversations are different."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

At the first sign of engine trouble, you diverted to the nearest airport with maintenance capability. You prioritized getting the airplane in front of a mechanic over getting yourself to the destination. The mechanic found a sticking exhaust valve — a progressive failure that would have continued to worsen, potentially leading to partial engine failure in flight.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This is excellent decision-making. You assessed the situation (engine roughness with a worsening trend on the EGT), evaluated your options (nearest airport vs. airport with maintenance vs. destination), and chose the option that addressed both the immediate safety concern and the underlying problem.

The decision to divert to Enid rather than Kingfisher showed good prioritization — you accepted a longer flight (35nm vs. 20nm) in exchange for landing at a facility that could diagnose and fix the problem. With the engine still making power and the symptoms not rapidly deteriorating, this was a well-calibrated risk decision.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This is what it looks like. First sign of trouble, divert to maintenance, ground the airplane. The added nuance of choosing Enid over Kingfisher — farther but with real capability — demonstrates mature risk assessment. You didn't just land at the first available runway; you landed at the first available <em>solution</em>.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

When the engine tells you something is wrong, listen. Land where someone can fix it. The wedding will still be there. The airplane needs to be there next week, too.
</div>

