:: D2-QuickLook [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Mechanic found valve — aircraft grounded"])>>
The lineman gives you a look — not judgmental, just knowing. "I'll get him."

The A&P comes out and listens to your description. He pulls the top cowl. Fifteen minutes later, he's looking at you with the same expression the lineman had.

"Exhaust valve on three. It's sticking. You're grounded."

"Can you—"

"No. This isn't a quick fix. I need to pull the cylinder. Two days minimum."

You stand on the ramp and look at the 182, cowl panels off, one cylinder exposed, and you think about the rehearsal dinner. And then you think about what Linda — the A&P — said next: "The good news is you flew it here. The bad news is it was going to get worse. If you'd tried to make Clinton-Sherman..." She shrugs. "Maybe you make it. Maybe you don't."

You rent a car. You make the wedding.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You diverted to Enid at the first sign of trouble — a sound decision. At the FBO, you asked for a "quick look," hoping to continue the flight. The mechanic found a sticking exhaust valve and grounded the aircraft. The outcome is the same as if you'd committed to grounding the airplane on arrival, but your hesitation at the FBO reveals a subtle continuation bias that survived the diversion.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

The diversion itself was excellent. The moment at the FBO — asking if the mechanic could look at it "quickly" because you were trying to get to Clinton-Sherman — is worth examining. You had already made the right decision by diverting. But part of you was still hoping the problem would be simple enough to fix and continue. This is <strong>residual continuation bias</strong>: the destination pressure survived the diversion and resurfaced when you were on the ground.

This didn't cause harm in this case — the mechanic made the call, and you accepted it. But in a different scenario, with a less decisive mechanic or a more ambiguous finding, that pressure to continue might have tipped the scale.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

When you divert for an engine problem, arrive at the FBO with the mindset that you are done flying today. Let the mechanic's diagnosis be what it is, without timeframe pressure. "Can he look at it quickly?" changes the dynamic — it tells the mechanic you're hoping for a certain answer, and it subtly pressures the process toward speed over thoroughness.

The better framing: "We have a rough-running engine. We need a full diagnosis. We'll arrange ground transportation while you work."

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

A diversion isn't complete when the wheels touch down. It's complete when you've fully committed to being on the ground for as long as the airplane needs to be on the ground.
</div>

