<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: E-Precautionary [scenario branch-e]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 2000)>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" volume 0.4 play>><</if>>
You pull the throttle back to eighteen inches. The engine note drops and the airspeed bleeds off — you slow to ninety knots, then eighty-five. You trim for a descent, about five hundred feet per minute. You have altitude to spend and you intend to spend it carefully.

"Kansas City Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we have a rough-running engine. We're descending for a precautionary landing, approximately fifteen miles northeast of Kingfisher. Squawking seventy-seven hundred."

"November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger, squawk seven-seven-zero-zero confirmed. Say souls on board and fuel remaining."

"Two souls, four-eight gallons."

"Copy. Nearest airport is Kingfisher, one-five miles to your southeast, or Enid Woodring, three-two miles to your north. Emergency services have been notified for the Kingfisher area. Will you be able to maintain radio contact?"

"We'll try. We're descending through five thousand now."

Linda's hand is on the armrest. She's looking out the window at the ground coming up, and then she looks at you. "Tell me what's happening."

"The engine isn't running right. I'd rather land in a field while I have choices than wait until I don't have choices."

She nods once. "Okay."

Below you, the terrain is everything you need it to be right now. Flat. Open. Wheat stubble in every direction, section-line roads running ruler-straight north-south and east-west. A few farmsteads, a grain elevator on the horizon, power lines along one of the roads. The kind of country where you could land a 182 on almost any quarter-section and walk away.

You pass through three thousand feet AGL. The wind is out of the southwest and you can see its effect on the dust rising from a field being plowed a mile or so to the east. You're going to want to land to the south or southwest, into the wind.

As you descend through two thousand feet, three things present themselves:

A section-line road below you runs perfectly straight north-south for at least half a mile. Paved. No visible power lines crossing it. A farmhouse about a quarter mile east. No traffic that you can see.

To your left, a recently harvested wheat field stretches out wide and flat. The stubble is short. The soil looks firm — it hasn't rained recently. There's room for three runways in there.

And to the east, about three miles, you can see something you didn't expect — a grass runway with a windsock. A private strip, neat and maintained, with a metal hangar at the south end. It's not on your chart, but someone flies out of there. You have the altitude and the engine to reach it.

<<link "You line up on the section-line road. Straight, flat, no power lines, into the wind. It's narrow — maybe eighteen feet — but the 182's gear track is about ten. You can do this." "E1-Road">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed on section-line road"])>><</link>>

<<link "You set up for the wheat field. It's the biggest, most forgiving surface you can see. If the gear digs in, you'll deal with it. At least you won't run out of room." "E2-WheatField">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed in wheat field"])>><</link>>

<<link "You turn toward the private grass strip. A real runway, with a windsock and a hangar. Three miles east. You have the altitude, and the engine is still running." "E3-PrivateStrip">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed on private grass strip"])>><</link>>

:: E1-Road [scenario branch-e ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Safe road landing — aircraft intact"])>>
You set up a final approach to the road from the south, into the wind. Sixty-five knots over the fence — there is no fence, just a ditch on either side and flat wheat stubble beyond. You hold the wings level with the crosswind, keep the nose straight with rudder, and touch down on the pavement.

The road is narrow. The main gear straddles the center stripe with a foot to spare on each side. The nosewheel tracks straight. You brake gently and the 182 rolls to a stop in about eight hundred feet.

You're sitting on a county road in Kingfisher County, Oklahoma, with the engine idling and a wheat field on either side. The engine is still running, still rough, still making power. You shut it down.

The silence is total. Then a meadowlark starts up somewhere in the stubble.

Linda looks at you, and then she looks out the window at the road stretching away in both directions, and then she starts laughing. Not nervous laughter. Real laughter. "I can honestly say I have never landed on a road before."

"Me neither."

A pickup truck appears from the farmhouse a quarter mile away. The rancher pulls up, leans out the window, and looks at the airplane parked on his road with an expression that suggests this isn't the strangest thing he's seen this week. "Engine trouble?"

"Exhaust valve, I think. Rough-running."

"Well, you picked a good road for it. Nothing comes through here except my cows, and they're in the south pasture." He looks at the airplane again. "You want some coffee while you wait for whoever you're going to call?"

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

At the first sign of engine trouble, you chose to make a precautionary landing rather than continue to your destination or divert to an airport. You descended with the engine still producing power, selected a section-line road, and executed a controlled landing. The aircraft is undamaged. Both occupants are unharmed.

This is a precautionary landing in the purest sense — a deliberate decision to land while you still have altitude, engine power, and choices, rather than waiting for the situation to deteriorate.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

This is the most conservative response to the engine roughness, and it is a defensible one. With the engine still making power and airports within range, many pilots would have chosen to divert to Kingfisher or Enid. Your decision to land immediately reflects a risk tolerance that strongly favors certainty over efficiency — and in aviation, that risk tolerance keeps people alive.

The road landing itself was well-executed: you verified no power lines, checked for traffic, landed into the wind, and maintained directional control on a narrow surface.

Some may argue this was an overreaction — the engine was still running, and airports were available. That's a fair discussion. But the design philosophy behind your decision ("I'd rather land with choices than without them") is exactly the kind of thinking that prevents the accidents where the pilot ran out of options gradually and didn't realize it until too late.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

A precautionary landing is never wrong if it's executed safely. The question to carry forward is about calibration: what level of engine anomaly warrants a precautionary landing versus a diversion to an airport? That's a personal minimums question, and your answer today — "any anomaly I can't explain" — is a safe one.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

A precautionary landing with a running engine is always better than a forced landing with a dead one. If you're going to err, err toward the ground.
</div>

