<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: E2-WheatField [scenario branch-e ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Wheat field landing — minor gear damage"])>>
You set up a final approach into the wind, aiming for the center of the wheat field. The stubble is short — six inches, maybe eight — and the soil looks dry and firm. You carry a little extra speed, seventy knots over the threshold that doesn't exist, and flare.

The mains touch and the airplane decelerates immediately. The stubble grabs at the wheels. The nosewheel comes down and digs in slightly — the soil is firmer than plowed earth but softer than pavement. The airplane shudders and pulls to the left as the nosewheel tracks through a soft spot. You hold the rudder and the brakes, and the 182 comes to a stop in about four hundred feet.

The left main gear has sunk about three inches into the soil. The nosewheel is buried up to the axle. The prop is intact — it cleared the ground. But the airplane is sitting in a wheat field with its nose slightly down, and it's not going to taxi out of here.

You shut down. The engine coughs once and stops.

Linda looks at the wheat stubble pressing against the windows. "Are we stuck?"

"The airplane is. We're not."

You climb out. The air smells like cut wheat and engine oil. The gear appears intact — the nosewheel strut is compressed but not bent. The airplane will need to be lifted out of the soft spots and inspected, but it looks like cosmetic damage at worst.

A crop duster pilot lands on the section-line road twenty minutes later — he heard your radio call and came to check on you. He gives you and Linda a ride into Kingfisher in the back of his truck, and he doesn't stop grinning the whole way. "Best landing I've seen in a wheat field all year."

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

You made a precautionary landing in a wheat field with the engine still producing power. The landing was successful — both occupants walked away unharmed — but the soft soil caused the nosewheel to dig in, resulting in minor gear compression and a stuck aircraft. The airplane will require inspection and extraction but is likely repairable without major structural work.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

The decision to make a precautionary landing was sound. The field selection was reasonable — large, flat, and clear of obstacles. The soft soil was a known risk that you accepted. In an off-airport landing, surface conditions are always a variable, and wheat stubble over agricultural soil will always be softer than pavement.

A road or the private grass strip might have been a better surface choice — harder, flatter, and less likely to trap the gear. But field selection under pressure is never perfect, and a wheat field landing that you walk away from is a success by any meaningful measure.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

The precautionary decision itself was excellent. The field selection was adequate. For future reference: when multiple landing options present themselves during a precautionary descent, prioritize hard surfaces (roads, runways) over soft surfaces (fields, pastures) when they're equally accessible. The harder the surface, the more predictable the rollout.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

A precautionary landing you walk away from is a good landing, period. The airplane can be fixed. You can't.
</div>

