<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: E3-PrivateStrip [scenario branch-e ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed on private grass strip — best possible outcome"])>>
You turn east and descend toward the grass strip. It's about three miles, and from this altitude you can see it clearly — a mowed grass runway, oriented roughly north-south, maybe two thousand feet long. The windsock is showing the same southwest wind you've been dealing with all morning. A metal hangar sits at the south end, and there's a gravel drive leading to a farmhouse.

You enter the pattern on a midfield crosswind, fly a tight downwind, and turn base. The engine is still running, still rough, and for the first time you're glad it is — the power gives you options on final that a dead engine wouldn't. You carry seventy knots and touch down on the grass about two hundred feet in. The turf is firm and well-maintained. The 182 rolls straight and stops with a thousand feet to spare.

You park near the hangar and shut down. The wind whispers through the grass. The engine ticks as it cools.

A man in his sixties comes walking from the farmhouse, unhurried, with a blue heeler at his heels. He looks at the airplane, then at you and Linda climbing out, and nods.

"Engine trouble?"

"Rough-running. Cylinder three."

"Hmm." He looks at the cowl. "I'm retired Air Force — maintenance officer. Not current on my A&P, but I can tell you this: if it's rough on one cylinder in a Continental, you're either looking at a plug, a valve, or a fuel injector nozzle. If leaning didn't fix it, it's not the plug." He pauses. "You did the right thing putting it down."

He lets you use his phone, gives you and Linda sandwiches and iced tea on his porch, and drives you into Kingfisher in his truck when the rental car arrives. The mechanic from Enid confirms the sticking valve two days later. The airplane flies off the grass strip the following week with a new valve and a thank-you case of beer left in the hangar.

<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio ":engine" stop>><<audio "engine-fail" stop>><<audio "wind-quiet" stop>><<audio "field-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<div class="debrief">
---

<h3>What Happened</h3>

At the first sign of engine trouble, you chose a precautionary landing. During the descent, you identified a private grass strip — an unlisted runway maintained by a local landowner — and landed safely. The aircraft is undamaged. Both occupants are unharmed. The exhaust valve on cylinder three was later confirmed as sticking.

This is the best possible outcome from the precautionary landing branch. You combined the conservative decision to land immediately with the situational awareness to find a real runway instead of a field or road.

<h3>ADM Analysis</h3>

Every element of this decision chain was sound. You detected the anomaly, assessed the risk, and chose the most conservative course of action (land now) while maintaining the flexibility to improve your options during execution (finding the grass strip). This is <strong>dynamic decision-making</strong> at its best: a conservative strategy, executed with awareness and adaptability.

The decision to land at the private strip rather than the road or the field shows good judgment about surface selection — a maintained grass runway is the best off-airport surface available, combining the hard surface of a road with the width and clear approaches of a field.

<h3>What Good Judgment Looks Like Here</h3>

This is it. This is what decades of experience and good training look like in practice: a pilot who trusts his instincts, acts early, and keeps his eyes open for opportunities even while executing a conservative plan. The precautionary landing was the right call. The grass strip was a bonus that rewarded situational awareness.

<h3>Key Takeaway</h3>

Land while you have choices. And while you're descending, keep looking. The best option might be the one you haven't seen yet.
</div>

